commit_message:
[WIP] Resource tracker use compute_node obj

The resource tracker is being converted to use objects. This
patch converts the compute_node data structure (currently a
dict) to the compute_node object. Subsequent patches will
convert the service and instance objects.

The patch also updates some tests using fake resource trackers.

This is part of: blueprint make-resource-tracker-use-objects

Change-Id: Ib21abb35845a84e7dcbf18b1a901674fa90440fa

commit_message:
Proposed blueprint for live migration fixes in juno.

This blueprint isn't finished yet, in that it doesn't have an actual
design yet. However, I've done a survey of the outstanding live
migration bugs in nova, and its clear that we need to take a more
systematic approach to making live migration more reliable.

Change-Id: Ia6934d763621262417ac98e9fa1605d251b01bdd
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/nova-specs refs/changes/66/80866/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: Improve libvirt migration reliability ===================================== There are a lot of open live and block migration bugs recorded in LaunchPad. I believe the way forward is a systematic examination of the problems reported and then improving the code. One of the root causes of the unreliable nature of live migration is that we don't have testing for migrations in the gate. We need to address that as well. What's broken? -------------- OMG there are a lot of bugs reported about libvirt migration in nova. Whilst some of these bugs aren't valid, they all at the least describe scenarious we should test with tempest as users have had problems with them in the past. The bugs currently recorded in LaunchPad (as at March 2014) are: - Inconsistent virtual size in qcow base image after block-migration (bug/1237683): the underlying problem here is that we're creating the ephemeral backing files with an incorrect virtual size. - Live migration fails when the instance has a config-drive (bug/1246201, bug/1240877): libvirt has a bug where it doesn't migrate read-only devices. We need to use a disk device instead of a cdrom device for config drives. This bug already has a fix proposed at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/74848/ - Nova doesn't update vnc listen address during migration with libvirt (bug/1262450) and instance migration should not be allowed when there are open VNC sessions (bug/1240584, bug/1287101): nova should update VNC listen address in libvirt.xml to the destination node's vncserver_listen setting on completing migration. If there is a VNC (or any other console) session open when the live migration is initiated, the live migration should abort. - Live migration doesn't work with LVM (bug/1282643) [1] - Block live migration does not work when a volume is attached (bug/1276639) or when only volumes are attached to an instance (bug/1282506, bug/1250751): I am including RBD mounts as "volumes" here for the purposes of these bugs. - Nova quota statistics can be incorrect (bug/1284424), we don't always claim resources on the destination host (bug/1289064, bug/1260581), resource tracker fails after migration if instance is already tracked on destination node (bug/1278741). - Live migration doesn't respect memory over subscription (bug/1214943) - Live block migration results in loss of console log (bug/1203193). This one might not be fixable in the live migration code, but is discussed in the libvirt-serial-console blueprint. - Live migration failed because of file permission changed (bug/1252519): we appear to be mangling instance file permissions for live migrations on shared filesystems in some cases. The user reports problems with glusterfs, but it might happen with other file system types as well. - Nova libvirt driver live migration should sanitize target host (bug/1276862): we blindly trust the user supplied destination host name to be valid. - Live migration between hosts with differents CPU models fails (bug/1082414): the problem here is that there are two CPU models for each host - the model that the host pCPU has, and the model that the guest vCPU uses. The migration checks are comparing the host CPUs from the two machines. So they can compare as incompatible, even if you've explicitly configured the guest CPU to be a model that is a lowest common denominator. - Live block migration fails for instances whose glance images have been deleted (bug/1270825, bug/1206887) - Instance resize doesn't work after a live migration (bug/1240317) - Live migrate proceeds if the instance is locked (bug/1257187) - We fail to cleanup networking on the destination when we roll back a failed migration (bug/1284719) - Instance data resides on destination node when vm is deleted during live-migration (bug/1285000): we fail to cleanup the destination node when we abort a live migration because the instance was deleted. - Block migration _post_live_migration may run with an expired token (bug/1286142): the keystone token may expire during the time it takes to stream the instance disks to the destination host. There are also these bugs, which aren't specifically fixable by tweaking the libvirt migration code: - Insecure live migration with libvirt driver (bug/1240554): by default, libvirt on the receiving end of a live migration starts a qemu process listening on 0.0.0.0 waiting for a tcp connection from the sender. During block migration, qemu-nbd is started similarly. This is bad because compute nodes have interfaces on the guest network. As a result, guests can interfere with live migrations. What's the fix? --------------- Each of these bugs needs to be fixed, and in some cases its obvious that we need to do a bit of an audit to make sure we've covered all of the failure cases (even those not reported). Common classes of bug appear to be: - remote console connections need to either be terminated or migrated to the destination host. This is true for new types of consoles as we add them. - non-qemu storage migration (LVM, RBD, volumes) seem buggy. We need to audit these, as well as ensuring that any future ones are handled properly. This might require refactoring this disk code to make it obvious that storage authors need to handle the live migration case. - quota code needs an audit. - rollback needs an audit and better testing. Testing ------- In order to implement better testing for live migration we need multinode devstack to run in the gate. This isn't a problem for a nova blueprint, but I want to high light it as a need. Who would do this work? ----------------------- Michael Still is the author of this blueprint and intends to persue implementation in Juno. This one is pretty big though, so he'd love some help. Footnotes --------- 1: There is a fix currently proposed for this one in gerrit, but I haven't checked if it fixes all cases.

commit_message:
Fix missing reinterpolated log message

In the original GlanceClientWrapper.call method from nova.image.glance,
a "done trying" log message will never be produced. When attempt reach
num_attempts, "trying" message will still be logged, however the message
should be "done trying". Add reinterpolation logic of the log message
to fix that.

Closes-Bug: #1292993

Change-Id: Ie97704af7cfd14479dc0f9f23cdf79d3531a7c0f
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/nova refs/changes/45/81245/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: extra = "retrying" if attempt < num_attempts else "done trying" LOG.exception(error_msg) if attempt == num_attempts:
deleted_lines: extra = "retrying" if attempt == num_attempts: extra = 'done trying' LOG.exception(error_msg) LOG.exception(error_msg)

The memorycache module registers the option "memcached_servers" in the

commit_message:
Memorycache: Make opt group configurable in get_client

The memorycache module registers the option "memcached_servers" in the
default group. However, the keystoneclient auth middleware also
registers the option in a separate group. To allow the auth middleware
to unregister the option from the default group, we need to allow the
caller of get_client() to pass the group in which to find the config -
CONF by default, but CONF.keystone_authtoken in the case of the auth
middleware.

Partial-bug: #1262148

Change-Id: I76e794a1dd8bcf580784f0b11fa184577ab0518b
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/oslo-incubator refs/changes/12/81412/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: def get_client(memcached_servers=None, conf=CONF): memcached_servers = conf.memcached_servers

commit_message:
Support building wheels (PEP-427)

Universal is used to identify pure-Python module(by bdist_wheel). For
these, it is sufficient to build a wheel with _any_ Python ABI version
and publish that to PyPI (by whatever means).

Change-Id: I715a2a49636791cc45c95d6aed18213560ba40df
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/trove refs/changes/35/57135/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: [wheel] universal = 1

"""Unit tests for images prefetcher""" import mock from glance.common import exception from glance.image_cache import ImageCache from glance.image_cache.prefetcher import Prefetcher from glance.tests import utils class TestPrefetcher(utils.BaseTestCase): @mock.patch.object(ImageCache, 'init_driver') def setUp(self, mock_init_driver): super(TestPrefetcher, self).setUp() mock_init_driver.return_value = True self.prefetcher = Prefetcher() self.image_id = 2 @mock.patch.object(ImageCache, 'cache_tee_iter') @mock.patch('glance.registry.client.v1.api.get_image_metadata') @mock.patch('glance.context.RequestContext') @mock.patch('glance.store.get_from_backend') def test_fetch_image_into_cache(self, mock_get_from_backend, mock_RequestContext, mock_get_image_metadata, mock_cache_tee_iter): mock_get_image_metadata.return_value = {'status': 'active', 'location': '/v1', 'checksum': '8cde070'} mock_get_from_backend.return_value = ['some_data', '20g'] mock_cache_tee_iter.return_value = {'fake1': 'fake2'} mock_RequestContext.return_value = 'some_context' self.assertTrue(self.prefetcher.fetch_image_into_cache(self.image_id)) mock_get_image_metadata.assert_called_with('some_context', self.image_id) mock_get_from_backend.assert_called_with('some_context', '/v1') mock_cache_tee_iter.assert_called_with(self.image_id, 'some_data', '8cde070') @mock.patch('glance.registry.client.v1.api.get_image_metadata') @mock.patch('glance.context.RequestContext') def test_fetch_image_into_cache_exception(self, mock_RequestContext, mock_get_image_metadata): mock_get_image_metadata.side_effect = exception.NotFound mock_RequestContext.return_value = 'some_context' self.assertFalse(self.prefetcher.fetch_image_into_cache(self.image_id)) mock_get_image_metadata.assert_called_with('some_context', self.image_id) @mock.patch('glance.registry.client.v1.api.get_image_metadata') @mock.patch('glance.context.RequestContext') def test_fetch_image_into_cache_wrong_status(self, mock_RequestContext, mock_get_image_metadata): mock_get_image_metadata.return_value = {'status': 'none'} mock_RequestContext.return_value = 'some_context' self.assertFalse(self.prefetcher.fetch_image_into_cache(self.image_id)) mock_get_image_metadata.assert_called_with('some_context', self.image_id) @mock.patch.object(ImageCache, 'get_queued_images') @mock.patch.object(Prefetcher, 'fetch_image_into_cache') def test_run(self, mock_fetch_image_into_cache, mock_get_queued_images): mock_get_queued_images.return_value = [1, 2, 3] mock_fetch_image_into_cache.return_value = True self.assertTrue(self.prefetcher.run()) mock_fetch_image_into_cache.assert_called_with(3) @mock.patch.object(ImageCache, 'get_queued_images') def test_run_no_images(self, mock_get_queued_images): mock_get_queued_images.return_value = None self.assertTrue(self.prefetcher.run()) @mock.patch.object(ImageCache, 'get_queued_images') @mock.patch.object(Prefetcher, 'fetch_image_into_cache') def test_run_wrong_images_number(self, mock_fetch_image_into_cache, mock_get_queued_images): mock_get_queued_images.return_value = [1, 2, 3] mock_fetch_image_into_cache.return_value = False self.assertFalse(self.prefetcher.run()) mock_fetch_image_into_cache.assert_called_with(3)

commit_message:
Return correct messages to client

When HTTPUnprocessableEntity exception happens, client can only
receive the default error messages defined in the exception class,
that's not the client wants.
This patch makes the exception return correct messages.

Change-Id: I50f1432f12ef0940107bbfd26fa45c33749ae9b5
Closes-Bug: #1291726

commit_message:
Caught AttributeError when creating a role with bad request

When creating a role with a bad request body, AttributeError will
happen, but will not be caught. This will cause a 500 error.
This patch fixes this problem.

Closes-Bug: #1287471
Change-Id: Icd998f2edb7111b58bcbc23f0506d944c3425a26

commit_message:
Tox tests should not require errors in rigid order

Fix the tox tests to not require Validation Error messages to be returned
in a specific order. Since the order of validation errors can be
non-deterministic, the tests should merely check for existence of the error.

Change-Id: I615359cfb7129b2af9f22c43ad4475b53f7acab3
Closes-bug: 1294850

commit_message:
Plugin-based panel group configuration

Panels can be added through plugin configuration, but it is broken
if the user can only use existing panel groups. This adds the
capability to create an empty panel group that can be used by panel
configuration to add itself to the group.

Change-Id: I28d6072fc05b3a4ef5a41cd68337a7864c560525
Closes-Bug: #1287981

commit_message:
Make conductor expect ActionEventNotFound for action methods

The action_event_start() and action_event_finish() methods can
raise InstanceActionEventNotFound exceptions. Make sure these
get forwarded to the caller without logging them against the
conductor service.

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>
Change-Id: I4d0bf185f515efac0eaa5245e5270e6e1877d8da

Add tests for action_event_start/finish expected_exceptions

Adds some conductor unit tests for making sure expected exceptions in
action_event_start and action_event_finish are handled properly.

Change-Id: Ia6f622874a4419f96fec875bb92a4f677b646558

commit_message:
Don't log exception for None timeout_mins

If a request contains a timeout_mins key but it is None (which is
now the case for all requests sent via python-heatclient), we log
an exception, but really we just want to ignore the value and
continue (as well as other "None" values, ie '0' which was the
previous default for no key)

So split the test for a key and conversion to int, and only log
the exception if there is an error doing the type conversion,
not if we get a value which implies ignoring/doing nothing.

Change-Id: I6b8d1f053b47fd4c22a5df636481a95bd046b1df
Closes-Bug: #1297759

commit_message:
Remove obsolete po entries - they break translation jobs

The ironic-propose-translation-update job has been failing to update
from transifex because our .po files contain duplicates of obsolete
entries which were causing errors.

Change-Id: I41a056cbe10096c07e7682d8d79ff8f8c58ad3e2
Related-bug: #1298645

[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-28 08:40:09.000000000', 'files': ['nova/openstack/common/rpc/impl_qpid.py'], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/nova/commit/ecb058de339da8ee828b629c072f4dbb8541fc74', 'message': "User a more accurate max_delay for reconnects

In an HA deployment, a 60 seconds delay between reconnects can be quite
problematic. This patch changes the delay calculation by setting the max
delay to 5s and by changing the way it is increased.

Unfortunately, this is one of the places where both our main drivers are
not consistent. Rabbit's driver uses configuration parameters for this
whereas qpid's driver has never had one. However, I would prefer not
adding configuration paremeters to qpid's driver for the following
reasons:

    1. Most of OpenStack services depend on the messaging layer, hence
    they need it to be available. A 5s delay seems to be reasonable and

commit_message:
User a more accurate max_delay for reconnects

In an HA deployment, a 60 seconds delay between reconnects can be quite
problematic. This patch changes the delay calculation by setting the max
delay to 5s and by changing the way it is increased.

Unfortunately, this is one of the places where both our main drivers are
not consistent. Rabbit's driver uses configuration parameters for this
whereas qpid's driver has never had one. However, I would prefer not
adding configuration paremeters to qpid's driver for the following
reasons:

    1. Most of OpenStack services depend on the messaging layer, hence
    they need it to be available. A 5s delay seems to be reasonable and
    I could argue the need of tune it further. Although so frequent
    reconnects can add load to the network, that wouldn't be the main
    issue if one of the brokers go down.
    2. We're trying to move away from configuration options towards using
    transport URL. This path is still not clear and I would
    prefer avoiding adding new options until we clear it out.

Closes-bug: #1281148

Change-Id: I537015f452eb770acba41fdedfe221628f52a920
(cherry picked from commit 8b628d1e024f787dbb93d508117d9148388c0590)
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/nova refs/changes/89/83689/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: delay = min(delay + 1, 5)

commit_message:
Safer noqa handling

"# flake8: noqa" was used in several files. This causes the
entire file to not be checked by flake8. This is unsafe, and
"# noqa" should be used only on those lines that require it.

E712 doesn't honor #noqa, so work around it by assigning True to a
variable.

Change-Id: I1ddd1c4f4230793f0560241e4559095cb4183d71

commit_message:
Refactors unit tests of image service detail()

We do not need to have "unit" tests that test the things like
pagination work with the glanceclient.images.detail() call. glanceclient
and glance have unit tests for that. What the unit tests for the glance
image service detail() method in Nova need is to test only the code
boundary that exists within the detail() method -- i.e. verify that the
calls to the glanceclient and other helper methods are made with the
right parameters.

This patch pulls the various unit tests out of the
TestGlanceImageService test class and into their own test class that
uses mocks and verifies each code path within the detail() method.

Next up is the create, update and delete methods of the
GlanceImageService class. The final piece is to rework the download unit
tests (which aren't unit tests but more functional tests that take
around a second each to run :(

Change-Id: I94897ff54a36a1af4258ba4a3c88b45c079f4bb5
Related-bug: #1293938

commit_message:
Refactors nova.image.glance unit tests for show()

This patches continues a patch series to cleanup and streamline the unit
tests for the nova.image.glance module. Here, we create true unit tests
for the GlanceImageService.show() method, stressing all code paths and
edges but only for that specific method, using mocks and no fake glance
image service.

This patch removes "unit" tests from the TestGlanceImageService that
called glance.GlanceImageService.show(), as those tests used the fake
glance service and the code paths are now more than covered by these new
mock-using tests.

Change-Id: I200a9e9812d6de011fa6faa8fb8dc570075ce902
Related-bug: #1293938

commit_message:
Enhance test to rescope token using v2

There was a problem in Keystone recently where revoking a token
derived from another token caused the original token to be
revoked, so adding a test here to validate it continues to work
as expected.

Change-Id: I4b6a1440b661c075793e73edc52b4a5919d93d71

added_lines: #!/usr/bin/python -u # Copyright (c) 2010-2012 OpenStack Foundation # # Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License"); # you may not use this file except in compliance with the License. # You may obtain a copy of the License at # # http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0 # # Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software # distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS, # WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or # implied. # See the License for the specific language governing permissions and # limitations under the License. import unittest import time from swiftclient import client from swift.common.manager import Manager from swift.obj import diskfile from swift.common import exceptions, utils from test.unit import DebugLogger from test.probe.common import reset_environment, get_server_number, \ get_to_final_state class TestObjectExpirer(unittest.TestCase): def setUp(self): self.expirer = Manager(['object-expirer']) self.expirer.start() if self.expirer.status(): raise unittest.SkipTest('Unable to start object-expirer') self.expirer.stop() (self.pids, self.port2server, self.account_ring, self.container_ring, self.object_ring, self.url, self.token, self.account, self.configs) = reset_environment() def tearDown(self): Manager(['all']).stop() def get_config(self, node): server, number = get_server_number(node['port'], self.port2server) return utils.readconf(self.configs['object-server'][number], section_name='object-replicator') def wait_for_object_to_expirer(self, container, obj_name, timeout=10): # wait for the object to expirer deadline = time.time() + timeout while time.time() < deadline: try: odata = client.get_object(self.url, self.token, container, obj_name)[-1] except client.ClientException as e: self.assertEquals(e.http_status, 404) break else: self.assertEqual(odata, 'VERIFY') time.sleep(1) else: self.fail('Object "%s" did not 404 before timeout (%ss)!' % (obj_name, timeout)) # wait for the object diskfile to be removed by the expirer path_parts = [self.account, container, obj_name] opart, onodes = self.object_ring.get_nodes(*path_parts) logger = DebugLogger() deadline = time.time() + timeout while time.time() < deadline: # run the expirer self.expirer.once() for node in list(onodes): conf = self.get_config(node) df_manager = diskfile.DiskFileManager(conf, logger) df = df_manager.get_diskfile(node['device'], opart, *path_parts) try: df.open() except exceptions.DiskFileExpired: # this isn't the exception we're looking for pass except exceptions.DiskFileDeleted: onodes.remove(node) if not onodes: break else: self.fail('DiskFile "%s" on %r did not raise Deleted ' 'before timeout (%ss)!' % (obj_name, node, timeout)) # it's hard to use the listing as proxy because we had container # failures """ # wait for the object to be removed from the listing deadline = time.time() + timeout while time.time() < deadline: self.expirer.once() else: self.fail('Object "%s" was still in container listing ' 'after timeout (%ss)!' % (obj_name, timeout)) """ def test_container_failures(self): # create a test container container = 'expiring-container-failures' client.put_container(self.url, self.token, container) # fail the first half of container servers container_server = Manager(['container']) first_half, second_half = (1, 3), (2, 4) for number in first_half: container_server.stop(number=number, wait=True) # create some objects to expire in the first half of containers first_objects = ['first-obj-%d' % i for i in range(8)] for i, obj in enumerate(first_objects): client.put_object(self.url, self.token, container, obj, 'VERIFY', headers={'x-delete-after': i + 1}) # start the first half of container servers back up for number in first_half: container_server.start(number=number, wait=True) # populate the .expiring_objects account container_updater = Manager(['container-updater']) container_updater.once() # wait for one of the objects to expire self.wait_for_object_to_expirer(container, first_objects[0]) # now kill the second half of servers for number in second_half: container_server.stop(number=number, wait=True) # now create some files not in the second half of servers second_objects = ['second-obj-%d' % i for i in range(4)] for i, obj in enumerate(second_objects): client.put_object(self.url, self.token, container, obj, 'VERIFY', headers={'x-delete-after': i + 1}) # start the second half of servers back up for number in second_half: container_server.start(number=number, wait=True) # create some more objects in all containers other_objects = ['other-obj-%d' % i for i in range(4)] for i, obj in enumerate(other_objects): client.put_object(self.url, self.token, container, obj, 'VERIFY', headers={'x-delete-after': i + 1}) container_updater.once() # wait for all the objects to expire for obj_list in (first_objects, other_objects, second_objects): for obj in obj_list: self.wait_for_object_to_expirer(container, obj) get_to_final_state() headers, listing = client.get_container(self.url, self.token, container) object_listing = [o['name'] for o in listing] for obj_list in (first_objects, other_objects, second_objects): for obj_name in obj_list: if obj_name in object_listing: self.fail('Found listing for %s in %s' % (obj_name, container)) if __name__ == "__main__": unittest.main()

commit_message:
Sync common db code from Oslo

This sync contains commit ``f7705f3 Make table utf-8 charset
checking be optional for DB migration`` which will be used to
support bug #1279000 fix.

Full list of changes:

9fed4ed Fix Keystone doc build errors with SQLAlchemy 0.9
f7705f3 Make table utf-8 charset checking be optional for DB migration
5b7e61c Dispose db connections pool on disconnect
d1988b9 Set sql_mode callback on connect instead of checkout
a1a8280 Fix excessive logging from db.sqlalchemy.session
dc2d829 Add lockutils fixture to OpportunisticTestCase
d10f871 Adapt DB provisioning code for CI requirements
5920bed Make db utils importable without migrate
9933bdd Get mysql_sql_mode parameter from config
96a2217 Prevent incorrect usage of _wrap_db_error()
6cab37c Python3: define a __next__() method for ModelBase
20a7510 Add from_config() method to EngineFacade

Change-Id: I115f5610101a8512af484111469f5060dce27919
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

added_lines: from glance.openstack.common.gettextutils import _LE, _LW assert issubclass( self.__class__, sqlalchemy.orm.session.Session ), ('_wrap_db_error() can only be applied to methods of ' 'subclasses of sqlalchemy.orm.session.Session.') # if the database server has gone away, all connections in the pool # have become invalid and we can safely close all of them here, # rather than waste time on checking of every single connection engine.dispose() # this will be handled by SQLAlchemy and will force it to create # a new connection and retry the original actiondef _set_session_sql_mode(dbapi_con, connection_rec, sql_mode=None): server default. cursor = dbapi_con.cursor() cursor.execute("SET SESSION sql_mode = %s", [sql_mode]) def _mysql_get_effective_sql_mode(engine): """Returns the effective SQL mode for connections from the engine pool. Returns ``None`` if the mode isn't available, otherwise returns the mode. """ # Get the real effective SQL mode. Even when unset by # SQL mode as set by the server configuration. # Also note that the checkout listener will be called on execute to # set the mode if it's registered. row = engine.execute("SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'sql_mode'").fetchone() if row is None: return return row[1] def _mysql_check_effective_sql_mode(engine): """Logs a message based on the effective SQL mode for MySQL connections.""" realmode = _mysql_get_effective_sql_mode(engine) if realmode is None: LOG.debug('MySQL server mode set to %s', realmode) "consider enabling TRADITIONAL or STRICT_ALL_TABLES"), realmode) def _mysql_set_mode_callback(engine, sql_mode): if sql_mode is not None: mode_callback = functools.partial(_set_session_sql_mode, sql_mode=sql_mode) sqlalchemy.event.listen(engine, 'connect', mode_callback) _mysql_check_effective_sql_mode(engine) idle_timeout=3600, if mysql_sql_mode: _mysql_set_mode_callback(engine, mysql_sql_mode) 1. commit_message:
User a more accurate max_delay for reconnects

In an HA deployment, a 60 seconds delay between reconnects can be quite
problematic. This patch changes the delay calculation by setting the max
delay to 5s and by changing the way it is increased.

Unfortunately, this is one of the places where both our main drivers are
not consistent. Rabbit's driver uses configuration parameters for this
whereas qpid's driver has never had one. However, I would prefer not
adding configuration paremeters to qpid's driver for the following
reasons:

    1. Most of OpenStack services depend on the messaging layer, hence
    they need it to be available. A 5s delay seems to be reasonable and
    I could argue the need of tune it further. Although so frequent
    reconnects can add load to the network, that wouldn't be the main
    issue if one of the brokers go down.
    2. We're trying to move away from configuration options towards using
    transport URL. This path is still not clear and I would
    prefer avoiding adding new options until we clear it out.

Closes-bug: #1281148

Change-Id: I537015f452eb770acba41fdedfe221628f52a920
(cherry picked from commit 8b628d1e024f787dbb93d508117d9148388c0590)

commit_message:
Import request_id middleware bug fix from oslo

There is a bug in request-id middleware that a subsequent API request
will overwrite a request-id of a previous request when multiple API
calls are processed in parallel in request_id middleware. The fix is
a drop-in replacement; cinder code does not need to be modified to
use the updated request_id middleware.

oslo change to fix the middleware:
d7bd9dc37ac3d6bc171cd2e290c772633ad20a32

Closes-Bug: #1289696
Change-Id: Ib211318c47681f841bcde04e490ccc2070bdf8de

commit_message:
Use a dequeue instead of recursion

A dequeue will scale better for large scheduling
graphs vs recursion (which will only scale as far as
pythons stack size is set to).

Change-Id: I02fe6cb984628a3776bbef236602860aca27beb8

added_lines: Ceilometer ========== #### Table of Contents 1. [Overview - What is the ceilometer module?](#overview) 2. [Module Description - What does the module do?](#module-description) 3. [Setup - The basics of getting started with ceilometer](#setup) 4. [Implementation - An under-the-hood peek at what the module is doing](#implementation) 5. [Limitations - OS compatibility, etc.](#limitations) 6. [Development - Guide for contributing to the module](#development) 7. [Contributors - Those with commits](#contributors) 8. [Release Notes - Notes on the most recent updates to the module](#release-notes) Overview -------- The ceilometer module is part of [Stackforge](https://github.com/stackforge), an effort by the OpenStack infrastructure team to provice continuous integration testing and code review for OpenStack and OpenStack community projects not part of the core software. The module itself is used to flexibly configure and manage the metering service for OpenStack. Module Description ------------------ The ceilometer module is an attempt to make Puppet capable of managing the entirety of ceilometer. This includes manifests to provision the ceilometer api, agents, and database stores. A ceilometer_config type is supplied to assist in the manipulation of configuration files. Setup ----- **What the ceilometer module affects** * ceilometer, the metering service for OpenStack ### Installing ceilometer example% puppet module install puppetlabs/ceilometer ### Beginning with ceilometer Implementation -------------- ### ceilometer ceilometer is a combination of Puppet manifests and Ruby code to deliver configuration and extra functionality through types and providers. Limitations ----------- * The ceilometer modules have only been tested on RedHat and Ubuntu family systems. Development ----------- Developer documentation for the entire puppet-openstack project * https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet-openstack#Developer_documentation Contributors ------------ * https://github.com/stackforge/puppet-ceilometer/graphs/contributors This is the ceilometer module. Release Notes ------------- ** 3.1.0 ** * Fixed package ceilometer-alarm type error on Debian. * Remove log_dir from params and make logs configurable in init. * Removed glance_notifications from notification_topic. * Don't match commented [DEFAULT] section. ** 3.0.0 ** * Initial release of the puppet-ceilometer module.

commit_message:
Improve generic cleanup performance

* Added @cleanup decorator which wraps scenario methods requiring
a resources cleanup. Using @cleanup(['nova', 'cinder']) will only
clean the resources of specified components, it improves rally
performance since we avoid unnecessary clean of resources that
was done in previous design.
* Updated cleaner context to fit the above requirements:
if a scenario method doesn't use @cleanup, the cleaner context
will clean all the resources (like it was done before), otherwise
it will clean the resources of components specified in parameter of
the decorator.

Partially implements: blueprint benchmark-context-improve-cleaner
Change-Id: Ifc23c3a72777a24471bf279e059eae207785132e

commit_message:
When extracting deployments, don't delete original

Previously the entire deployments section was deleted, which contains data that
other configuration tools need such as inputs and outputs schemas.

This change leaves the entire deployments section in place for other tools which
are expecting be able to access this data (namely, the heat-config hooks)

Change-Id: I40c11f2387eac2a684e8ed98817eefa107ea651a

Remove advertise-host from service file

The regex used is environment-specific, let's just not pass this
argument for now (it's optional).

commit_message:
Avoid traceback with insufficient auth credentials

Raise an exception if configured credentials are not sufficient
for obtaining an endpoint and token.

Change-Id: Ie11a25eb67da2d2c2c8ef40ab984eb2ecb77fdf9
Closes-Bug: 1290601

commit_message:
Write a dpkg manifest to list installed packages

To create an auditable log of packages installed in an image use
dpkg-query to create a json data file with the package names, version
and install status.

Change-Id: I59018221edcb944a876ad47b402538c63c426bc7

subject: Fix segment allocation tables in Cisco N1kv plugin
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-06 03:13:17.000000000', 'files': [], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/neutron/commit/b0a4a0a8e7f2184696e825390330f1e0c0f3e053', 'message': 'Use segment range from network profile tables for N1k plugin

The segment ranges for VLAN and VXLAN are being populated using an in memory dictionary.
Use the segment range from the network profile table instead.
By using the network profile UUID as a foreign key in the segment allocations table,
clean up is easier and consistent.

'}, {'number': 5, 'created': '2014-03-11 01:05:26.000000000', 'files': [], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/neutron/commit/04dc18e806a9e6f9e89e99d3d388ee4c0e473057', 'message': 'Fix segment allocation tables in Cisco N1kv plugin

The segment allocation table is emptied on deleting any network profile.
This change allows the use of segment range from the network profile table.
By using the network profile UUID as a foreign key in the segment allocations table,
tables are cleaned up only for the segments associated with
the deleted network profile via CASCADE, leaving no inconsistencies.

Change-Id: I507041fac3768a7b688ddcf28c4d97c618bfe3f9
Closes-Bug: #1288407

commit_message:
Fix segment allocation tables in Cisco N1kv plugin

The segment allocation table is emptied on deleting any network profile.
This change allows the use of segment range from the network profile table.
By using the network profile UUID as a foreign key in the segment allocations table,
tables are cleaned up only for the segments associated with
the deleted network profile via CASCADE, leaving no inconsistencies.

Change-Id: I507041fac3768a7b688ddcf28c4d97c618bfe3f9
Closes-Bug: #1288407

commit_message:
Cleanup ldap tests (mox and reset values)

When running concurrent test workers, the structure used to test
the instantiation of the FakeLdap handler was relying on mox. In
some cases the test structures were not reset during teardown.

The test cases were not clearing out the _HANDLERS in the common
ldap module. This has been corrected with an addCleanup and moving
the setUp logic to the BaseLDAPIdentity class instead of the
LDAPIdentity class.

Change-Id: I2976774dabeb2b9196b3f25c02838bf4c4688d94

commit_message:
Fix error when run with no arguments on Python 3

Python 3 changed the map built-in to return an iterable instead of a list.
When tested in a boolean context, this always returns True, even if it
would not return anything when iterated.

Instead of the usage being printed, this error was printed:
ERROR: 'Namespace' object has no attribute 'func'

Use list comprehension instead to ensure that an iterable isn't returned

Change-Id: Ie15f2fa8ee93ab26490e371133fa0f944430737b
Closes-bug: 1295356

Check domain_id with equality in assignment kvs

It was noticed in https://review.openstack.org/70816 that the kvs
assignment backend was using a contains check instead of an equality
check which comparing domain_ids.

commit_message:
Remove releases.rst from keystone docs

The most recent update to releases.rst was made back in 2012,
but it's references in the docs page. It is providing false
(or at least, inaccurate) information. Suggest removing it
since the server side doesn't have a release related file either.

Change-Id: If2a71b55117c450afdade3cad697eba5a626263f

commit_message:
Expand the use of non-ascii values in ldap test

Very few of the ldap tests were using non-ascii values, in fact
non-ascii values were restricted to only specific tests that
had 'unicode' in their test name. This is very weak test coverage.

This patch replaces all occurances of 'fake1', the standard string
used in the tests for test value with 'fäké1' where the a has an
umlaut and the e has a diacritical. Visually they look almost the
same but will trigger the type of encoding exceptions we've seen
in the past.

Closes-Bug: 1172106

Change-Id: I03b10f3da93a8fb388baacb00532c03019f327c0

commit_message:
Properly handle unicode & utf-8 in LDAP

This patch adds all the necessary type conversions between the LDAP
API's.

* string literals are unicode

* unicode strings are utf-8 encoded before calling LDAP

* utf-8 strings received from the LDAP API are decoded into unicode

* string classes use the six.text_type for Python 2 vs. Python 3
  compatibility

* the fake LDAP implementation was reworked such that it's external
  API only handles UTF-8 encoded strings but only uses unicode
  internally. This is because internally it must be able to operate on
  logical characters in order to perform string operations on it's
  data. This is very much akin to what happens in a real LDAP
  implementation, the interface is UTF-8 but operations occur on
  decoded logical characters.

Unicode tests that were skipped are now re-enabled.

Partial-Bug: 1172106
Change-Id: Icce6b508f748214e241de40c3c9389b2caccea83

commit_message:
Use correct variable for host_access dependency

The keystone::db::mysql resource declares resources using
`$real_allowed_hosts` which is a copy of `$allowed_hosts` minus `$host`.
But then it declares dependencies using `$allowed_hosts` which includes
`$host` and will fail catalog compilation due to a missing dependency

This bug only affects users if the value of `$host` is included in the
array of `$allowed_hosts`

Change-Id: Ifdd8793bcf36178efd1a083ee35649d56dc3d768
(cherry picked from commit 7813820abd30e77c6119e11d390237c1e6978086)

commit_message:
Use correct variable for host_access dependency

The keystone::db::mysql resource declares resources using
`$real_allowed_hosts` which is a copy of `$allowed_hosts` minus `$host`.
But then it declares dependencies using `$allowed_hosts` which includes
`$host` and will fail catalog compilation due to a missing dependency

This bug only affects users if the value of `$host` is included in the
array of `$allowed_hosts`

Change-Id: Ifdd8793bcf36178efd1a083ee35649d56dc3d768

commit_message:
Cleanup revocation query

The code in the revoke sql backend to calculate the query for the
list of events was creating a temporary and then discarding it,
and blaming not using it on sqlite.

Rather than discard the temporary, a reference is kept to it so
that it can be used.

Change-Id: Ifdb6a70900af85869b43d319eab8aa2a6b2bc162

deleted_lines: query.filter(RevocationEvent.revoked_at >= last_fetch) # While the query filter should handle this, it does not # appear to be working. It might be a SQLite artifact. events = [model.RevokeEvent(**e.to_dict()) for e in query if e.revoked_at > last_fetch] else: events = [model.RevokeEvent(**e.to_dict()) for e in query]

commit_message:
Exception when scheduling task with invalid state

Since GraphAnalyzer checks for tasks and retries to be scheduled we
have to raise an exception when it tries to schedule a task with
invalid state.

Change-Id: Ib9eb1ffaf7d0d1b3fd6a9b49504ef508778dd3ee

commit_message:
Fix test_provider_token_expiration_validation transient failure

The keystone.tests.test_token_provider.TestTokenProvider.
test_provider_token_expiration_validation test would fail if the
tests weren't run before the expiration period passed. This could
happen if the system was slow and the previous tests took a long
time causing a potential transient failure.

Change-Id: I123aadd55770002fe1c9ed9b17669d5212198aa3
Closes-Bug: #1278550

commit_message:
Remove "exit 0" from prepare script

docker/prepare script is sourced from a another script

the exit 0 instruction was causing the whole script to exit, not
only the docker/prepare script.
Also change a "cd" to a "pushd" and "popd"

Change-Id: I1af230f341cdc0f7209e59894fdd9cfd827d43e9

added_lines: <section xml:id="section_networking-api-ssl"> <title>Configuring SSL Support for Networking API</title> <para>OpenStack Networking supports SSL for the API Server. This feature is disabled by default but it can be easily enabled in the neutron.conf file.</para> <para>These are the variables needed for configuring SSL support.</para> <variablelist> <varlistentry> <term>use_ssl = False</term> <listitem> <para>Enable SSL on the API server.</para> </listitem> </varlistentry> <varlistentry> <term>ssl_cert_file = /path/to/certfile</term> <listitem> <para>Certificate file to use when starting API server securely.</para> </listitem> </varlistentry> <varlistentry> <term>ssl_key_file = /path/to/keyfile</term> <listitem> <para>Private key file to use when starting API server securely.</para> </listitem> </varlistentry> <varlistentry> <term>ssl_ca_file = /path/to/cafile</term> <listitem> <para>CA certificate file to use when starting API server securely to verify connecting clients. This is an optional parameter only required if API clients need to authenticate to the API server using SSL certificates signed by a trusted CA.</para> </listitem> </varlistentry> <varlistentry> <term>tcp_keepidle = 600</term> <listitem> <para>Sets the value of TCP_KEEPIDLE in seconds to use for each server socket when starting API server. Not supported on OS X.</para> </listitem> </varlistentry> <varlistentry> <term>retry_until_window = 30</term> <listitem> <para>Number of seconds to keep retrying to listen.</para> </listitem> </varlistentry> <varlistentry> <term>backlog = 4096</term> <listitem> <para>Number of backlog requests to configure the socket with.</para> </listitem> </varlistentry> </variablelist> </section>

commit_message:
remove dump tables from previous migrations

dump tables from 012 and 027 migrations should really be handled
by DBAs. creating additional dump tables just consumes unnecessary
space.

Change-Id: I3a8716627c2f52a1a3c59f36009d8265ac96a0fa
Closes-Bug: #1259724

commit_message:
Support building wheels (PEP-427)

Universal is used to identify pure-Python module(by bdist_wheel). For
these, it is sufficient to build a wheel with _any_ Python ABI version
and publish that to PyPI (by whatever means).

Change-Id: I900a7d2e3777a5c151778679f3049771047855e6

commit_message:
Fixed possible pep8 failure due to pyflakes bug

There is a bug in pyflakes that may trigger F811 violation when import
is not used in a file before its redefinition in local class method
scope, even though it's used in other classes later in the same file.

Change-Id: Ie611e2ff93c59b01a2695c3d944cfe118f874547
Related-Bug: #1297161

commit_message:
Fixed inconsistent EventletContextManagerSpawnTest failures

The test spawns a greenthread and expects it to complete after
eventlet.sleep(0) call. The problem is that if there are other
greenthreads currently running, sleep(0) may switch to unexpected
thread, which may result in test thread not being invoked at all.
Instead of assuming no other green threads are running at the moment
of test execution, explicitly wait() for the test thread.

Change-Id: Id45307860733658638b74ed3a713493df8c1080d
Closes-Bug: #1282706

commit_message:
Correct two bugs with neutron router gateway id parsing

1. The regex ended with `\}` but in the case of external gateways such
   as `{"network_id": "8b43562d-f168-4317-8c9f-4d639ba126ea", "enable_snat": true}`
   this was not finding the network_id.
2. The `.*` was greedy and in the prior case, matching more than just
   the id.

Change-Id: I224c0bcf387434bdd029b4c80934a66b60cc77e0
(cherry picked from commit c8989e62a51b22acf4f7862aa56bf574e9ac19f3)

commit_message:
Don't override the policy files in the local settings

The setting override currently doesn't add anything (the file names are
kept the same) but causes new files added upstream to be missed as the
entire POLICY_FILES dictionary is being overriden.

Change-Id: I2ce4cace705e89ef2fbb4a2f4e57c9074fc512ac
Closes-Bug: #1296636

commit_message:
if log_file enabled, ensure log_dir is not absent

If log_file is specified, that means we should configure log_dir.
Otherwise, when running a command which use debug (like db-sync commands), it will try to write logs in the user directory which is not the best way.

This patch aims to ensure that we configure log_dir instead of remove
the flag like it was before.

Partial-bug #1292619
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Change-Id: I94528b42a4865976f74d264facd91cb521c177bd
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/puppet-neutron refs/changes/62/81662/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: 'DEFAULT/log_file': value => $log_file; 'DEFAULT/log_dir': value => $log_dir;

commit_message:
Create ingress spoofing rules

This will ensure the DST_IP is in fact
the IP nova assigned to the VM.

Should help mitigate bug #1274034
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1274034)

Change-Id: If2db4413d5750581cae6b21366f0d9ea1bd63048
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/neutron refs/changes/99/83799/2 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: table.add_rule(chain_name, '-d %s/32 -j RETURN' % (ip)) ipv4_sg_rules, port, "4", direction) ipv6_sg_rules, port, "6", direction) def _convert_sgr_to_iptables_rules(self, security_group_rules, port, proto_version, direction): if proto_version == "4" and direction == INGRESS_DIRECTION: self._drop_ingress_spoofing_rules(iptables_rules, port) def _drop_ingress_spoofing_rules(self, iptables_rules, port): chain_name = self._port_chain_name(port, SPOOF_FILTER) iptables_rules += ['-j $%s' % (chain_name)]
